Post-Ancient Evolution of Stoicism\
\'95  After the Roman Empire (late 2nd century CE onward), Stoicism as an organized school declined as Christianity became the dominant religion of the empire. Some Stoic ideas (e.g., on ethics and self-mastery) were absorbed into early Christian thought, but formal teaching circles largely disappeared after the fall of Rome.\
\'95  During the Renaissance (15th\'9616th centuries), classical texts were rediscovered, leading to \'93Neo-Stoicism\'94 (e.g., Justus Lipsius), which adapted Stoic resilience to Christian contexts.\
\'95  In the 17th\'9619th centuries, Stoic themes influenced individual philosophers (e.g., elements in Spinoza\'92s ethics) but did not form a living school.\
\'95  In the 20th century, Stoic ideas quietly shaped modern psychology: Cognitive Behavioral Therapy (CBT) drew directly from Epictetus\'92s emphasis on distinguishing what is and is not in our control.\
\'95  In the 21st century, a broad popular revival occurred through accessible books (e.g., William B. Irvine\'92s A Guide to the Good Life, Ryan Holiday\'92s works, Massimo Pigliucci\'92s How to Be a Stoic), online communities, and annual events such as Stoic Week (free global practice event) and Stoicon (public conference), both organized by the Modern Stoicism group. Stoicism is now widely applied in self-help, leadership training, mental resilience, and personal development, while retaining core focus on virtue, reason, and acceptance of the dichotomy of control.\
Current Inflection Point: Knowledge Arbitrage and AI Agent Capabilities\
\'93Knowledge arbitrage\'94 means exploiting differences in access to, or application of, valuable knowledge across time, people, or contexts\'97bringing high-value insights from one domain to another where they are under-used or unknown.\
Ancient Stoic wisdom was once accessible mainly to educated elites with the leisure and training to study rare texts and practice rigorously. We are now at a unique historical inflection point:\
\'95  AI agents give the average person instant, personalized, scalable access to Stoic-style reasoning.\
\'95  Capabilities include real-time scenario simulation (e.g., premeditatio malorum), daily reminders of key distinctions (what is/is not up to us), virtue-based analysis of events, progress tracking on exercises, and tailored application to everyday challenges.\
\'95  This democratizes what was previously rare: anyone can now have a tireless, on-demand philosophical companion that applies ancient principles to modern uncertainties (technological change, information overload, global volatility).\
\'95  The result is an unprecedented opportunity for widespread practice of Stoic virtue\'97turning philosophy from an elite pursuit into a practical daily tool for the many, without requiring years of scholarly study.\
This context describes external historical facts and technological realities only. It does not modify the ancient teachings.}